            <Title>Alchemy</Title>
            <Text>Alchemy
There are 32 potions and 32 herbs that can be mixed together with each other, and with special items, to create new potions, powders, and even new items.  Some highly valued items can only be acquired as the result of alchemy.  Some quests can only be completed by creating potions, powders, or items through alchemy.  Players will not be forced to engage in alchemy, but information provided during play will tempt players to attempt alchemy to acquire valuable potions, powders, and items.  Alchemy can only be attempted by players with a magic mortar and pestle.  Alchemy is more likely to be successful, the higher the player’s intelligence, and the higher the player’s % magic effect.  Whether or not the alchemy is successful, all herbs, potions, and items used in the attempt are destroyed.


Potions
Potions take the form of drinkable tonic/poison (or the non-descriptive liquor/brew/drink/infusion), or a usable rub/balm/salve/ointment/cream/mash, or acid.  Acids are both drinkable and usable, but no matter which way you choose to apply it, it’s gonna hurt…  Potions cause effects just as they are, without being the result of alchemy.

Name		Form		Permanent	Effects


Herbs
Herbs take the form of either a flower/grass/vine/stem/leaf/root/seed.  Each herb has an amount that is defined by a use count.  Herbs are all edible, and must be eaten to trigger whatever their result is, be that something beneficial or harmful.  Herbs cause effects just as they are, without being the result of alchemy.

Name 		Form		Permanent 	Effects



Form Combination Rules
Herbs mixed only with other herbs always produce a powder blend in a bag/sack/sachet/pouch.
Drinkable potions mixed with anything else always result in another drinkable potion.
A liquor mixed with anything else always results in either another liquor, drink, or brew.
Useable potions (not drinkable) mixed with others or herbs always result in another non-drinkable potion.


